<subSubSection id="C36F6539FF91447EEED66F4FFE26FE9F" box="[151,472,330,357]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BCA36B2FF91447EEED66F4FFE26FE9F" blockId="2.[151,472,330,357]" box="[151,472,330,357]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<heading id="D08281DEFF91447EEED66F4FFE26FE9F" bold="true" box="[151,472,330,357]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEED66F4FFE26FE9F" bold="true" box="[151,472,330,357]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
Systematics of 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEF106F4FFE26FE9F" authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1855" box="[337,472,330,357]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEF106F4FFE26FE9F" bold="true" box="[337,472,330,357]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36F6539FF91447EEED66F97FA95FA3A" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCA36B2FF91447EEED66F97FDE1FE56" blockId="2.[151,1437,402,1473]" box="[151,543,402,428]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEED66F97FE83FE56" bold="true" box="[151,381,402,428]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Molecular analyses</emphasis>
(see Figure 1)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCA36B2FF91447EEED66FB3FD63FCEF" blockId="2.[151,1437,402,1473]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
The Bayesian analysis reveals a well supported (PP = 1.0) monophyletic 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EED9C6FB3FBA5FE2A" authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1855" box="[989,1115,438,464]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EED9C6FB3FBA5FE2A" box="[989,1115,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade compared to our nine outgroup taxa (Fig. 1). The mtDNA (COI) gene supports the morphological distinction of our two new species that are clearly differentiated from the other 32 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EECCE6FFBFC96FDE2" box="[655,872,510,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EECCE6FFBFCF3FDE2" box="[655,781,510,536]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in our analysis, which are all defined by unique morphological characters (see Taxonomy section below). For species represented by multiple individuals, we found close intraspecific sequence divergences (Supplementary 
<tableCitation id="C6F70309FF91447EED3E6C43FC19FD9A" box="[895,999,582,608]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,239,460,486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 1. Specimen data for species identification, location of specimens, GenBank accession numbers or BOLD process IDs and collection data for all specimens listed in Figure 1." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF0A663AFF974478EED66FC9FF06FDF0" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" tableUuid="DF0A663AFF974478EED66FC9FF06FDF0">Table S1</tableCitation>
). For example, the greatest sequence divergences observed within any of our 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEC1A6C6FFCCFFD7E" box="[603,817,618,644]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEC1A6C6FFD27FD7E" box="[603,729,618,644]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
varied up to 1.7% for 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEA706C6EFAABFD7E" authority="(Tindale, 1941)" baseAuthorityName="Tindale" baseAuthorityYear="1941" box="[1073,1365,618,645]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karnka">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEA706C6EFB61FD7E" box="[1073,1183,618,645]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. karnka</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEAEC6C6FFAB3FD7E" author="Tindale, N. B." box="[1197,1357,618,644]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="15 - 46" refId="ref13500" refString="Tindale, N. B. (1941) Revision of the Australian Ghost Moths (Lepidoptera, Homoneura, Family Hepialidae) Part IV. Records of the South Australian Museum, VII (1), 15 - 46." type="journal article" year="1941">Tindale, 1941</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 1.4% for 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEEFE6C8AFE2EFD52" authority="(Tindale, 1932)" baseAuthorityName="Tindale" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[191,464,654,681]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furva">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEEFE6C8AFEE7FD52" box="[191,281,654,681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. furva</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEF696C8BFE36FD52" author="Tindale, N. B." box="[296,456,654,680]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="500 - 505" refId="ref13458" refString="Tindale, N. B. (1932) Revision of the Australian Ghost Moths (Lepidoptera, Homoneura, Family Hepialidae) Part I. Records of the South Australian Museum, IV (4), 500 - 505." type="journal article" year="1932">Tindale, 1932</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, and 1.5% for 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEC356C8AFBD0FD52" authority="Moore &amp; Edwards, 2014" authorityName="Moore &amp; Edwards" authorityYear="2014" box="[628,1070,654,681]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lineacurva">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEC356C8AFCF5FD52" box="[628,779,654,681]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. lineacurva</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EED536C8AFBD0FD52" author="Moore, M. D. &amp; Edwards, E. D." box="[786,1070,654,681]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="29 - 44" refId="ref13008" refString="Moore, M. D. &amp; Edwards, E. D. (2014) Two new species of Abantiades Herrich-Schaffer (Lepidoptera: Hepialidae) from Western Australia. Australian Entomologist, 41, 29 - 44." type="journal article" year="2014">Moore &amp; Edwards, 2014</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
); variation that we expect within species reported elsewhere for 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEFB56CB7FD85FD36" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[500,635,690,716]" class="Lepidoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="class">Lepidoptera</taxonomicName>
using the same COI gene (
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEDEE6CB6FC2EFD36" box="[943,976,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">e.g</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EED9E6CB6FB4CFD36" author="Beaver, E. P. &amp; Moore, M. D. &amp; Grehan, J. R. &amp; Velasco-Castrillon, A. &amp; Stevens, M. I." box="[991,1202,690,717]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="449 - 474" refId="ref11584" refString="Beaver, E. P., Moore, M. D., Grehan, J. R., Velasco-Castrillon, A. &amp; Stevens, M. I. (2020) Four new species of Splendid Ghost Moths (Lepidoptera: Hepialidae: Aenetus) from Australia and Papua New Guinea. Zootaxa, 4809 (3), 449 - 474. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4809.3.2" type="journal article" year="2020">
Beaver 
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEA776CB6FB91FD36" box="[1078,1135,690,716]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEAFC6CB6FA66FD36" author="Moore, M. D. &amp; Beaver, E. P. &amp; Velasco-Castrillon, A. &amp; Stevens, M. I." box="[1213,1432,690,717]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="71 - 93" refId="ref12861" refString="Moore, M. D., Beaver, E. P., Velasco-Castrillon, A. &amp; Stevens, M. I. (2020 b) Description of two new species of Abantiades Herrich-Schaffer (Lepidoptera: Hepialidae) and females of two further species with notes on their biogeography. Zootaxa, 4822 (1), 71 - 93. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4822.1.3" type="journal article" year="2020">
Moore 
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEB4E6CB6FABFFD36" box="[1295,1345,690,716]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">et al</emphasis>
. 2020 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEBCB6CB7FA66FD36" author="Parslow, B. A. &amp; Schwarz, M. P. &amp; Stevens, M. I." box="[1418,1432,690,716]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="253 - 264" refId="ref13048" refString="Parslow, B. A., Schwarz, M. P. &amp; Stevens, M. I. (2021) Molecular diversity and species delimitation in the family Gasteruptiidae (Hymenoptera: Evanioidea). Genome, 64 (3), 253 - 264. https: // doi. org / 10.1139 / gen- 2019 - 0186" type="journal article" year="2021">b</bibRefCitation>
</bibRefCitation>
, 2021). However, sequence divergences have been found to vary outside these ranges for some 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEA876CD3FA62FD0A" box="[1222,1436,726,752]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEA876CD3FABAFD0A" box="[1222,1348,726,752]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEEDE6CFFFE6EFCEE" author="Simonsen, T. J. &amp; Moore, M. D. &amp; Dupont, S. T. &amp; Stevens, M. I." box="[159,400,762,788]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="792 - 799" refId="ref13237" refString="Simonsen, T. J., Moore, M. D., Dupont, S. T. &amp; Stevens, M. I. (2019) Testing DNA barcodes against morphology for the ' tripectinate Abantiades ' (Lepidoptera: Hepialidae) reveals a complex relationship between COI sequence data and morphology. Austral Entomology, 58, 792 - 799. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / aen. 12395" type="journal article" year="2019">
Simonsen 
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEF576CFEFEB0FCEE" box="[278,334,762,788]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEFDD6CFEFD8DFCEE" author="Moore, M. D. &amp; Beaver, E. P. &amp; Velasco-Castrillon, A. &amp; Stevens, M. I." box="[412,627,762,789]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="115 - 141" refId="ref12788" refString="Moore, M. D., Beaver, E. P., Velasco-Castrillon, A. &amp; Stevens, M. I. (2020 a) Four new species of tri-forked Abantiades Herrich- Schaffer (Lepidoptera: Hepialidae) from the &quot; dark obscura clade &quot;. Zootaxa, 4801 (1), 115 - 141. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4801.1.5" type="journal article" year="2020">
Moore 
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEFAC6CFEFDD8FCEE" box="[493,550,762,788]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">et al.</emphasis>
2020a
</bibRefCitation>
, b).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCA36B2FF91447EEE866D1BFED3FBCF" blockId="2.[151,1437,402,1473]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
Sequence divergence comparisons among the 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EECA56D1BFC3FFCC2" box="[740,961,798,824]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EECA56D1BFC9CFCC2" box="[740,866,798,824]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, compared to our outgroup taxa, ranged between 6.2–16.0% (Supplementary 
<tableCitation id="C6F70309FF91447EEC0F6D47FD44FCA6" box="[590,698,834,860]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,239,460,486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 1. Specimen data for species identification, location of specimens, GenBank accession numbers or BOLD process IDs and collection data for all specimens listed in Figure 1." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF0A663AFF974478EED66FC9FF06FDF0" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" tableUuid="DF0A663AFF974478EED66FC9FF06FDF0">Table S1</tableCitation>
). Examining between 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EED8E6D47FB50FCA6" box="[975,1198,834,860]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EED8E6D47FBB3FCA6" box="[975,1101,834,860]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in Figure 1 reveal interspecific sequence divergences of up to 13.5% (
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEC9C6D62FCFBFC7A" box="[733,773,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">e.g.</emphasis>
between 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EED306D62FB1EFC7A" authority="(T. P. Lucas, 1898)" baseAuthorityName="T. P. Lucas" baseAuthorityYear="1898" box="[881,1248,870,897]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnificus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EED306D62FBF2FC7A" box="[881,1036,870,897]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. magnificus</emphasis>
(T.P. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEA0C6D62FB26FC7A" author="Lucas, T. P." box="[1101,1240,870,897]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="59 - 86" refId="ref12724" refString="Lucas, T. P. (1898) Descriptions of Queensland Lepidoptera. Proceedings of the Royal Society of Queensland, 13, 59 - 86." type="journal article" year="1898">Lucas, 1898</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEB596D62FEC4FC5E" authority="Tindale, 1932" authorityName="Tindale" authorityYear="1932" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericatus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEB596D62FA62FC7A" box="[1304,1436,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. sericatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEED66D8FFEC4FC5E" author="Tindale, N. B." box="[151,314,906,932]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="500 - 505" refId="ref13458" refString="Tindale, N. B. (1932) Revision of the Australian Ghost Moths (Lepidoptera, Homoneura, Family Hepialidae) Part I. Records of the South Australian Museum, IV (4), 500 - 505." type="journal article" year="1932">Tindale, 1932</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
). We also observed much lower interspecific sequence divergences in some cases, for example between 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEEBF6DAAFD80FC33" authority="(Donovan, 1805)" baseAuthorityName="Donovan" baseAuthorityYear="1805" box="[254,638,942,969]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="labyrinthicus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEEBF6DAAFE4DFC32" box="[254,435,942,969]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. labyrinthicus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEF856DABFD88FC33" author="Donovan, E." box="[452,630,942,969]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="38" refId="ref11867" refString="Donovan, E. (1805) s. n. In: Bensley, T., An epitome of the natural history of the insects of New Holland, New Zealand, New Guinea, Otaheite and other islands in the Indian, Southern, and Pacific Oceans: including figures and descriptions of one hundred and fifty-three species of the more splendid, beautiful, and interesting insects, hitherto discovered in those countries and which for the most parts have not appeared in the works of any preceding author. Printed for the author, and F. C. and J. Rivington, sold also by White, Faulder, Hatchard, and Symonds, London, pl. 38. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 123219" type="book chapter" year="1805">Donovan, 1805</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EECF86DAAFBEDFC32" authority="Simonsen, 2018" authorityName="Simonsen" authorityYear="2018" box="[697,1043,942,969]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mcquillani">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EECF86DAAFCADFC32" box="[697,851,942,969]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. mcquillani</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EED1D6DABFBEDFC32" author="Simonsen, T. J." box="[860,1043,942,968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" refId="ref13172" refString="Simonsen, T. J. (2018) Splendid Ghost Moths and their Allies, A Revision of Australian Abantiades, Oncopera, Aenetus, Archaeoaenetus and Zelotypia (Hepialidae). In: Monographs on Australian Lepidoptera. Vol. 12. CSIRO Publishing, Melbourne, pp. 1 - 300. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / 9781486307487" type="book" year="2018">Simonsen, 2018</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(2.2%) (Supplementary 
<tableCitation id="C6F70309FF91447EEB6F6DABFA6CFC32" box="[1326,1426,942,968]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,239,460,486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 1. Specimen data for species identification, location of specimens, GenBank accession numbers or BOLD process IDs and collection data for all specimens listed in Figure 1." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF0A663AFF974478EED66FC9FF06FDF0" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" tableUuid="DF0A663AFF974478EED66FC9FF06FDF0">Table S1</tableCitation>
) that may warrant further examination with more complete distributional sampling. However, similar patterns have been observed in some other ghost moths with each corresponding to clear morphological differences (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEB136DF2FEDFFBCF" author="Moore, M. D. &amp; Beaver, E. P. &amp; Velasco-Castrillon, A. &amp; Stevens, M. I." pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="71 - 93" refId="ref12861" refString="Moore, M. D., Beaver, E. P., Velasco-Castrillon, A. &amp; Stevens, M. I. (2020 b) Description of two new species of Abantiades Herrich-Schaffer (Lepidoptera: Hepialidae) and females of two further species with notes on their biogeography. Zootaxa, 4822 (1), 71 - 93. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4822.1.3" type="journal article" year="2020">
Moore 
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEED66A1EFF31FBCE" box="[151,207,1050,1076]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">et al.</emphasis>
2020b
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCA36B2FF91447EEE866A3BFA95FA3A" blockId="2.[151,1437,402,1473]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
Our new 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEF716A3BFDDCFBA3" box="[304,546,1086,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undefined-A">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEF716A3BFE50FBA2" box="[304,430,1086,1112]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades</emphasis>
species 
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEC4F6A3AFDDCFBA3" box="[526,546,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEC626A3AFD7BFBA2" box="[547,645,1086,1113]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">. malleus</emphasis>
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EECCD6A3BFD18FBA2" bold="true" box="[652,742,1086,1112]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23257DBFF91447EECCD6A3BFD18FBA2" box="[652,742,1086,1112]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
groups with 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EED3A6A3AFB58FBA2" authority="Tindale, 1932" authorityName="Tindale" authorityYear="1932" box="[891,1190,1086,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marcidus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EED3A6A3AFBFFFBA2" box="[891,1025,1086,1113]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. marcidus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEA496A3BFB58FBA2" author="Tindale, N. B." box="[1032,1190,1086,1112]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="500 - 505" refId="ref13458" refString="Tindale, N. B. (1932) Revision of the Australian Ghost Moths (Lepidoptera, Homoneura, Family Hepialidae) Part I. Records of the South Australian Museum, IV (4), 500 - 505." type="journal article" year="1932">Tindale, 1932</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, its nearest neighbour (Fig. 1; PP &lt;0.7), by 5.6–6.1% sequence divergence. 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EED486A67FC19FB86" authority="Moore &amp; Beaver &amp; Bradford &amp; Hutchinson &amp; Kay &amp; Temby &amp; Hamon &amp; Stevens, 2022" authorityName="Moore &amp; Beaver &amp; Bradford &amp; Hutchinson &amp; Kay &amp; Temby &amp; Hamon &amp; Stevens" authorityYear="2022" box="[777,999,1122,1148]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="malleus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EED486A67FC19FB86" box="[777,999,1122,1148]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades malleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEDB06A67FBB3FB86" bold="true" box="[1009,1101,1122,1148]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23257DBFF91447EEDB06A67FBB3FB86" box="[1009,1101,1122,1148]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is quite distinct by sequence divergence of the mtDNA (COI) gene (Supplementary 
<tableCitation id="C6F70309FF91447EED406A83FC9AFB5A" box="[769,868,1158,1184]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,239,460,486]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 1. Specimen data for species identification, location of specimens, GenBank accession numbers or BOLD process IDs and collection data for all specimens listed in Figure 1." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF0A663AFF974478EED66FC9FF06FDF0" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" tableUuid="DF0A663AFF974478EED66FC9FF06FDF0">Table S1</tableCitation>
), but in a clade with 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEA126A82FB27FB5A" authorityName="Tindale" authorityYear="1932" box="[1107,1241,1158,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marcidus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEA126A82FB27FB5A" box="[1107,1241,1158,1185]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. marcidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEAA66A82FEACFB3E" authority="(Swinhoe, 1892)" baseAuthorityName="Swinhoe" baseAuthorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albofasciatus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEAA66A82FA62FB5A" box="[1255,1436,1158,1185]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. albofasciatus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEEDE6AAFFEB5FB3E" author="Swinhoe, C." box="[159,331,1194,1220]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" refId="ref13414" refString="Swinhoe, C. (1892) Catalogue of eastern and Australian Lepidoptera Heterocera in the collection of the Oxford University Museum. Part 1. Sphinges and Bombyces'. Clarendon Press, Oxford, viii + 324 pp., 8 pls." type="book" year="1892">Swinhoe, 1892</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, and a species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEFB86AAEFDAFFB3E" baseAuthorityName="Tindale" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[505,593,1194,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furva">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEFB86AAEFDAFFB3E" box="[505,593,1194,1221]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. furva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the latter species once placed in the synonymised 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEA3C6AAFFB26FB3E" authorityName="Tindale" authorityYear="1932" box="[1149,1240,1194,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Bordaia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEA3C6AAFFB26FB3E" box="[1149,1240,1194,1220]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Bordaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 1). Pairwise comparisons between our second new species 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EECE16ACAFCCEFB12" authority="Moore &amp; Beaver &amp; Bradford &amp; Hutchinson &amp; Kay &amp; Temby &amp; Hamon &amp; Stevens, 2022" authorityName="Moore &amp; Beaver &amp; Bradford &amp; Hutchinson &amp; Kay &amp; Temby &amp; Hamon &amp; Stevens" authorityYear="2022" box="[672,816,1230,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="concordia" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EECE16ACAFCCEFB12" box="[672,816,1230,1257]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. concordia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EED766ACBFC6FFB12" bold="true" box="[823,913,1230,1256]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23257DBFF91447EED766ACBFC6FFB12" box="[823,913,1230,1256]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
to its nearest neighbour 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEAE76ACAFF27FAF6" authority="(Tindale, 1932)" baseAuthorityName="Tindale" baseAuthorityYear="1932" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxa">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEAE76ACAFACEFB12" box="[1190,1328,1230,1257]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. paradoxa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEB7E6ACBFF2EFAF6" author="Tindale, N. B." pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="500 - 505" refId="ref13458" refString="Tindale, N. B. (1932) Revision of the Australian Ghost Moths (Lepidoptera, Homoneura, Family Hepialidae) Part I. Records of the South Australian Museum, IV (4), 500 - 505." type="journal article" year="1932">Tindale, 1932</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 1; PP = 1.0) reveals between 4.1–5.0% sequence divergence. 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEDFF6AF7FB4DFAF6" authority="Moore &amp; Beaver &amp; Bradford &amp; Hutchinson &amp; Kay &amp; Temby &amp; Hamon &amp; Stevens, 2022" authorityName="Moore &amp; Beaver &amp; Bradford &amp; Hutchinson &amp; Kay &amp; Temby &amp; Hamon &amp; Stevens" authorityYear="2022" box="[958,1203,1266,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="concordia" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEDFF6AF7FB4DFAF6" box="[958,1203,1266,1292]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades concordia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEAF86AF7FAEFFAF6" bold="true" box="[1209,1297,1266,1292]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A23257DBFF91447EEAF86AF7FAEFFAF6" box="[1209,1297,1266,1292]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
conforms to Tindale’s morphological diagnosis for the synonymised ‘Bordaia’ (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEDC66B13FBE0FACA" author="Tindale, N. B." box="[903,1054,1302,1328]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="500 - 505" refId="ref13458" refString="Tindale, N. B. (1932) Revision of the Australian Ghost Moths (Lepidoptera, Homoneura, Family Hepialidae) Part I. Records of the South Australian Museum, IV (4), 500 - 505." type="journal article" year="1932">Tindale 1932</bibRefCitation>
) and does group with two species previously in that genus (
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEFF46B3EFDC1FAAE" box="[437,575,1338,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxa">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEFF46B3EFDC1FAAE" box="[437,575,1338,1365]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. paradoxa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEC366B3EFD1AFAAE" baseAuthorityName="Tindale" baseAuthorityYear="1941" box="[631,740,1338,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="karnka">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEC366B3EFD1AFAAE" box="[631,740,1338,1365]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. karnka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (Fig. 1). However, no close relationship was observed in our analysis to, or between, the other species (
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEC276B5AFD41FA82" baseAuthorityName="Tindale" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[614,703,1374,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furva">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEC276B5AFD41FA82" box="[614,703,1374,1401]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. furva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EECB36B5AFC05FA82" authority="(Tindale, 1932))" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Tindale" baseAuthorityYear="1932" box="[754,1019,1374,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pica">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EECB36B5AFCBEFA82" box="[754,832,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">A. pica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EED0C6B5BFC17FA82" author="Tindale, N. B." box="[845,1001,1374,1400]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" pagination="500 - 505" refId="ref13458" refString="Tindale, N. B. (1932) Revision of the Australian Ghost Moths (Lepidoptera, Homoneura, Family Hepialidae) Part I. Records of the South Australian Museum, IV (4), 500 - 505." type="journal article" year="1932">Tindale, 1932</bibRefCitation>
))
</taxonomicName>
previously in ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEAE16B5BFB05FA82" authorityName="Tindale" authorityYear="1932" box="[1184,1275,1374,1400]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Bordaia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEAE16B5BFB05FA82" box="[1184,1275,1374,1400]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Bordaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, and likewise the species previously in ‘ 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEF866B86FDDAFA66" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1890" box="[455,548,1411,1436]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Trictena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEF866B86FDDAFA66" box="[455,548,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Trictena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ although forming a poorly supported monophyletic clade but are embedded within 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF91447EEEA76BA3FE9AFA3A" authorityName="Herrich-Schaffer" authorityYear="1855" box="[230,356,1446,1472]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF91447EEEA76BA3FE9AFA3A" box="[230,356,1446,1472]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="203">Abantiades</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 1) and provides further support for the synonymy of both genera by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF91447EEAE26BA3FA98FA3A" author="Simonsen, T. J." box="[1187,1382,1446,1472]" pageId="2" pageNumber="203" refId="ref13172" refString="Simonsen, T. J. (2018) Splendid Ghost Moths and their Allies, A Revision of Australian Abantiades, Oncopera, Aenetus, Archaeoaenetus and Zelotypia (Hepialidae). In: Monographs on Australian Lepidoptera. Vol. 12. CSIRO Publishing, Melbourne, pp. 1 - 300. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / 9781486307487" type="book" year="2018">Simonsen (2018)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
